## Purpose

This policy sets out how **{{COMPANY_NAME}}** ("the company") handles the matter described above. It is binding on directors, employees and contractors. It is also relevant to customers and suppliers where it touches on their dealings with us.

The policy exists to protect the company, the team and our customers. It is not a substitute for common sense or for legal advice; where the two conflict, the policy is the floor, not the ceiling.

## Scope and application

This policy applies in every country in which {{COMPANY_NAME}} operates and to every contract under which we act, irrespective of the role or seniority of the individual concerned. Where local law sets a higher standard than this policy, local law wins.

Where this policy refers to a procedure, the procedure is a binding part of the policy. Where it refers to a guideline, the guideline is advisory and the policy owner can authorise an exception in writing.

## Access control

Production access requires (a) named user, (b) MFA, (c) a current engagement with the company, and (d) a documented business reason. Shared accounts are not permitted; the system named in the *Tool Stack Register* is used to issue temporary credentials when needed.

Joiners are granted access at onboarding. Movers have their access re-issued by the receiving team and the prior team revokes it. Leavers have their access revoked at offboarding within one hour of the engagement ending.

## Reporting concerns and breaches

Anyone who becomes aware of a breach of this policy — whether by themselves or someone else — must report it to the policy owner immediately. Reports can be made by email, by a 1:1 with a director, or anonymously via the channel described in the *Whistleblowing Policy*.

Breaches are investigated proportionately. The outcome is recorded; the identity of a good-faith reporter is protected as far as the law and the investigation permit. Retaliation against a good-faith reporter is itself a breach of this policy.

